  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 채시(綵侍) : '
    value: 초(楚)나라 노래자(老萊子)가 늙으신 부모를 즐겁게 하기 위해 채색이 화려한 색동옷을 입고 춤을 추며 어리광을 부렸다는 고사를 가리킴. 자식이 부모를 봉양함을 뜻함.
english:
  title: A Record of Baduk Stones
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My late father showed little interest in the arts, yet with baduk alone he grasped something of its essence—so much so that the skilled players of his time would sometimes yield to him. Yet no set remained in our household.

    When I became a mourning son and returned from the capital, my heart grew heavy with grief and I abandoned my studies. After completing the lesser mourning rites, as I was arranging my books, I discovered a set of baduk stones. Examining them, I found one made from shell—white ground with golden markings—and another of stone, smooth as jade and dark as ink, polished with such refinement that each stone gleamed round and perfect as a star. Surely these were treasures worthy of a scholar's table.

    Yet the set contained barely two hundred stones, and even with stones worn smooth by waves pressed into service, we could scarcely complete it. One day, my friend Sun came to call and said, "These I received from the monk Kaehong, who was serving your late father with devoted care. My son Ki presented them then." He counted them out and sighed, "At first there were three hundred sixty, abundant and whole. How is it that so few remain?"

    Seeing the melancholy in his expression, I fell into thought. Though these are but small things, they too must follow the course of fate—a truth the noble cannot ignore. Tracing them back: who first crafted them? Who first passed them on? From Kaehong to Sun, from Sun to me—and already we have lost half of what was lost before. Who will they pass to next? How gradually will they scatter? Into whose hands will they vanish entirely? Will scholars yet make use of them, or will they become mere playthings for the wealthy and dissolute? Pondering the past and present, considering the nature of things—how can one not weep?

    The principles of the round stones in motion and the square board at rest, the theories of weakness and strength—these I have no time to discuss. I record here: white stones—one hundred forty; black stones—one hundred nine. I have made two copies: one I send to Sun so he may know the path these stones have traveled, and one I keep to mark where they have come from. Thus I hope they will not be lost to time.
  footnotes:
    - The phrase 'serving with devoted care' alludes to a classical Chinese story of filial piety, where a child dressed in colorful garments and performed antics to bring joy to aging parents. Here it represents the son's service to the father.
    - The mention of 'half of what was lost before' reflects on the decay and loss that occurs through successive generations and hands—a meditation on impermanence that extends beyond mere objects to the human condition itself.
